Create the fastest possible single-file Java program named HashPrime.java that takes one integer N from the command line. Generate all prime numbers from 2 to N using a highly optimized Sieve of Eratosthenes. For every prime found, immediately convert it to its decimal string bytes followed by a single '\n' byte and feed it directly into a SHA-256 MessageDigest.update() call — do not use System.out, files, or any other I/O for the hashing path, as direct byte feeding into the digest is faster. After processing all primes, print only the final SHA-256 hexadecimal hash. The program must produce exactly this hash for both N=11 and N=12: 563d8e0603dcc07d784135d99fd81ff6bf98495e898ec1f52e2e7605320cf6dc.
